  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Increased access to quality education in a safe and protective learning environment for conflict affected children aged 3-18 in Dikwa LGA Borno State.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project is designed to focus on increasing access to quality education for conflict affected boys and girls, in a safe and protective learning environment. 
From the assessment conducted by ROHI at Dikwa, it was discovered that there were educational needs at Dikwa 
Dikwa is a local government area with several internally displaced persons, as a result camps have been set up to provide shelter for families. 
Most of the schools at Dikwa are closed down leaving only four functional schools. The functional schools do not have sufficient learning environment, and as a result, there is congestion in the classroom, while some of the learners do not go to the schools due to the distance from their camps.
It was observed that in most of the schools, children lack learning supplies and trained teachers.
For project implementation, ROHI will ensure that
a.	Conflict affected girls and boys have access to safe quality education in protective learning environment as well as latrines and water hand washing kits.
b.	Increased Quality training for Teachers and SBMC members in Dikwa. 
 
In order to achieve this, ROHI will conduct the following key activities. 

1. Establishment of safe and protective learning environment with separate latrines and water points for girls and boys. 
2. The supply of learning materials, for girls and boys, including hygiene kits for adolescent girls.  
3. Training of Teachers on Psycho social Support services and classroom management and pedagogy.  
4. Training of SBMCs to enhance the learning environment and protection of children. 

This project which targets four thousand (4,000) children of which all are IDPs residing at the camps, sixty (60) teachers and forty (40) SBMC members will be directly implemented by ROHI but in close coordination with UNICEF, EIEWG and other partners in Dikwa to avoid duplication of efforts while monitoring shall be done in coordination with the steering committee, NHF-HFU and the EIE Sector Working Group.</narrative>
  </description>
